The '''black-mantled goshawk''' ('''''Tachyspiza melanochlamys''''') is a species of [[bird of prey]] in the family [[Accipitridae]]. It is found in the highlands of [[New Guinea]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s. This species was formerly placed in the [[genus]] ''[[Accipiter]]''.

The black-mantled goshawk was figured in [[John Gould]]'s ''The Birds of New Guinea and the Adjacent Papuan Islands,'' where it was placed in the genus ''[[Astur (bird)|Astur]].''  The plate was prepared by [[William Matthew Hart]].<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1886 | title=The Birds of New Guinea and the Adjacent Papuan Islands: including many new species recently discovered in Australia | location=London | publisher=Henry Sotheran | at=Plate 1 and text  | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53841753 }}</ref>

==Taxonomy==
The black-mantled goshawk was [[species description|formally described]] in 1876 by the Italian zoologist [[Tommaso Salvadori]] based on a specimen collected in the [[Arfak Mountains]] of western New Guinea. He coined the [[binomial name]] ''Urospizias melanochlamys''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Salvadori | first=Tommaso | author-link=Tommaso Salvadori | date=1875 | publication-date=1876 | title=Descrizione di cinquantotto nuove specie di uccelli, ed osservazioni intorno ad altre poco note, della Nuova Guinea e di altre Isole Papuane, raccolte dal Dr. Opoarpo Reccari e dai cacciatori del Sig. A.A. Bruijn | language=Italian, Latin | journal=Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova | volume=7 | pages=896–976 [905] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/29836626 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1979 | title=Check-List of Birds of the World | volume=1 | edition=2nd | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=333 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/16108973 }}</ref> This species was formerly placed in the genus ''[[Accipiter]]''. In 2024 a comprehensive [[molecular phylogenetic]] study of the Accipitridae confirmed earlier work that had shown that the genus was [[polyphyletic]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Catanach | first1=T.A. | last2=Halley | first2=M.R. | last3=Pirro | first3=S. | date=2024 | title=Enigmas no longer: using ultraconserved elements to place several unusual hawk taxa and address the non-monophyly of the genus ''Accipiter'' (Accipitriformes: Accipitridae) | journal=Biological Journal of the Linnean Society | article-number=blae028 | doi=10.1093/biolinnean/blae028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last1=Mindell | first1=D. | last2=Fuchs | first2=J. | last3=Johnson | first3=J. | date=2018 | chapter=Phylogeny, taxonomy, and geographic diversity of diurnal raptors: Falconiformes, Accipitriformes, and Cathartiformes | editor1-last=Sarasola | editor1-first=J.H. | editor2-last=Grange | editor2-first=J.M. | editor3-last=Negro | editor3-first=J.J. | title=Birds of Prey: Biology and conservation in the XXI century | location=Cham, Switzerland | publisher=Springer | isbn=978-3-319-73744-7 | pages=3-32 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326086278 }}</ref> To resolve the non-[[monophyletic|monophyly]], ''Accipiter'' was divided into six genera. The genus ''[[Tachyspiza]]'' was resurrected to accommodate the black-mantled goshawk together with 26 other species that had previously been placed in ''Accipiter''. The resurrected genus had been introduced in 1844 by the German naturalist [[Johann Jakob Kaup]].<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela C. Rasmussen | date=August 2024 | title=Hoatzin, New World vultures, Secretarybird, raptors | work=IOC World Bird List Version 14.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/raptors/| publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=26 August 2024 }}</ref>  The genus name combines the [[Ancient Greek]] ταχυς (''takhus'') meaning "fast" with σπιζιας (''spizias'') meaning "hawk".<ref>{{ cite web | last=Jobling | first=James A. | title=Tachyspiza | work=The Key to Scientific Names | url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/key-to-scientific-names/search?q=Tachyspiza | publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology | access-date=26 August 2024 }}</ref> The specific epithet ''melanochlamys'' combines the [[Ancient Greek]] μελας (''melas''), μελανος (''melanos'') meaning "black" with χλαμυς (''khlamus''), χλαμυδος (''khlamudos'')  meaning "cloak" or "mantle".<ref>{{ cite web | last=Jobling | first=James A. | title=melanochlamys | work=The Key to Scientific Names | url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/key-to-scientific-names/search?q=melanochlamys | publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology | access-date=26 August 2024 }}</ref> 

This species has been treated as [[Polytypic taxon|polytypic]]; however, the more recent contention is that it is [[monotypic]], following Bruce Beehler and Thane Pratt.<ref name=beehler>{{ cite book | last1=Beehler | first1=B.M. | last2=Pratt | first2=T.K. | date=2016 | title=Birds of New Guinea: Distribution, Taxonomy, and Systematics | location=Princeton, New Jersey | publisher=Princeton University Press | isbn=978-0-691-16424-3 | page=211 }}</ref> The form ''schistacinus'' was described from Mount Goliath by [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Walter Rothschild]] and [[Ernst Hartert]] in 1913. They described this [[subspecies]] as being distinct from the nominate in "the black of the upperside, including wings and tail, having a decided greyish wash or bloom, so that, instead of being glossy black, the upper surface is slaty black, and the collar, and especially the underside, is distinctly paler, more cinnamon-chestnut than rufous-chestnut."<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Rothschild | first1=Walter | author1-link=Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild | last2=Hartert | first2=Ernst | author2-link=Ernst Hartert | year=1913 | title=List of the collections of birds made by Albert S. Meek in the lower ranges of the Snow Mountains, on the Eilanden River, and on Mount Goliath in the years 1910 and 1911 | journal=Novitates Zoologicae | volume=20 | pages=473-527 [482] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/15842894 }}</ref>  Beehler & Pratt  wrote that they did "not think this minor clinal distinction merits recognition."<ref name=beehler/>

